Univariate Analysis

In [17]:
# Performing only one thing(variable) at a time to perform Univariate analysis and show by countplot graph like :
  # by using Gender checking out of 1580 data how many have Male/Female candidates?
  # checking how many married or Single candidates out of 1580?
  # how many graduate or post graduates?
  # how many candidates are salaries OR Business candidates?
  # how much count of Hatchback/SUV/Sedan makers?
  # How much count of candidate having  personal loan?
  # or house loan
  # how much candidates having parner working ?

for cat_var in ["Gender","Marital_status","Education","Profession","Make","Personal_loan","House_loan","Partner_working"]:
    plt.Figure()
    sns.countplot(x=cat_var,data=df,)
    plt.title(f'Count of {cat_var}')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.show()
In [18]:
# Performing only one thing(variable) at a time to perform Univariate analysis and show by bar graph like :
  # count of age
  #count of depedent
  # salary range
  # Parner salary range
  # Family total salary range
  # price of car as per car model


for num_var in ["Age", "No_of_Dependents", "Salary","Partner_salary","Total_salary","Price"]:
    plt.Figure()
    sns.histplot(x=num_var,data=df,kde=True)
    plt.title(f'Count of {num_var}')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.show()

In [23]:
# Scatterplot
# It explain by age upto 30 most of prefer car price less than 40k / age group beween 20 to 46 prefer car price between 30k to 55 k and age group 35 to 60 prefer SUV for comfort
sns.scatterplot(x="Age", y="Price", hue="Make", data=df,alpha=0.7)
plt.title("Price vs Age scatterplot")
plt.show()
